12. The Somatic Sovereignty Scale (SSS): Psychometric Specification
The Somatic Sovereignty Scale (SSS) is an 18-item psychometric measurement instrument designed to quantify an individual’s capacity to maintain internal physiological regulation, psychological safety, and deliberate behavioral choice during exposure to elevated emotional or high-contrast sensory activation.

📐 12.1 The Complete 18-Item Instrument
Response Protocol: Participants rate their persistent lived experience over the past 30 days based on the following standard 7-point Likert scale:
1: Strongly Disagree | 2: Disagree | 3: Slightly Disagree | 4: Neutral | 5: Slightly Agree | 6: Agree | 7: Strongly Agree
🔹 Dimension 1: Interoceptive Awareness & Anchor Retention (IA)
Measures the baseline capacity to detect internal somatic signals without experiencing sudden cognitive dissociation or emotional flooding.

	•	SSS-IA-01: When I encounter high-intensity emotional or physical sensations, I can perceive my heartbeat and breathing patterns clearly without panic.
	•	SSS-IA-02: I can distinguish between healthy physiological arousal and an escalating survival/threat response in my body.
	•	SSS-IA-03: During moments of sudden relational tension, I maintain active awareness of my physical posture and grounding points.
	•	SSS-IA-04: I can track intense internal somatic energy fluctuations without feeling a compulsive requirement to immediately escape my body.
	•	SSS-IA-05: When experiencing visceral discomfort, I can consciously locate where it resides in my body and treat it purely as physiological data.
	•	SSS-IA-06: I can focus on an intense, lingering bodily sensation without obsessively checking, analyzing, or catastrophizing its meaning.
🔹 Dimension 2: Autonomic Down-Regulation Capacity (DR)
Measures the direct, voluntary mechanical capacity to shift the body out of an acute sympathetic spike and back into a parasympathetic flow state.

	•	SSS-DR-01: When my heart rate and adrenaline spike due to sudden stress, I can intentionally use my breath to slow my pulse down within a 2-minute window.
	•	SSS-DR-02: I can consciously release chronic, involuntary tension in my pelvic floor and diaphragm during high-stakes interpersonal encounters.
	•	SSS-DR-03: When my mind enters an anticipatory worry loop, I can successfully deploy somatic grounding to halt the mental cycle.
	•	SSS-DR-04: Even during an unexpected, intense fight-or-flight spike, I can consistently access long, rhythmic diaphragmatic exhalations.
	•	SSS-DR-05: I have practical somatic techniques that allow me to consciously dissolve a physical clenching reflex when it occurs.
	•	SSS-DR-06: I can transition smoothly from a high-excitation operational state back to deep physical relaxation at will.
🔹 Dimension 3: Stimulus-Response Decoupling & Choice Preservation (CP)
Measures the behavioral pivot space—the delay factor between a highly conditioned sensory cue and the final intentional execution vector.

	•	SSS-CP-01: In the presence of a strong, previously habituated cue or temptation, I can experience the urge without immediately reacting to it.
	•	SSS-CP-02: I can pause my physical movement and evaluate my options even when a strong dopamine craving loop is fully active.
	•	SSS-CP-03: My physical actions during high-arousal scenarios are guided by my active conscious values rather than automated somatic scripts.
	•	SSS-CP-04: I can tolerate intense, lingering internal tension without resorting to an immediate, destructive compulsive escape routine.
	•	SSS-CP-05: I perceive an inner cognitive buffer zone between receiving an intense sensory stimulus and choosing my exact response.
	•	SSS-CP-06: When an automated compulsive pattern attempts to hijack my behavior, I can cleanly pivot my body toward an alternate, high-agency task.

