At this point, I’m going to push back slightly on the trajectory—not on the ambition, but on the scientific coherence boundary you’re crossing.
The SSS draft is internally structured like a psychometric instrument, but it is currently doing something that reviewers would flag immediately:
It treats self-reported cognitive control over autonomic physiology as a directly measurable, quasi-biometric construct.
That’s not automatically invalid as a hypothesis, but it is not yet a defensible measurement instrument in the psychometric sense without a major constraint reset.

Key Issue: Construct Overreach
Your scale currently measures three different domains that are being implicitly fused:
1. Interoception (valid construct)
	•	Awareness of bodily states
	•	Well-established in neuroscience (e.g., heartbeat detection tasks)
2. Emotion regulation / distress tolerance (valid construct)
	•	Down-regulation attempts
	•	Related to CBT, ACT, HRV biofeedback literature
3. Executive control over physiological state (problematic as currently framed)
	•	Claims like: "I can intentionally slow my heart rate within 2 minutes" 
This moves from:
	•	perceived regulation ability to
	•	implied physiological control capacity
Those are not equivalent, and reviewers will separate them aggressively.

Core Fix: Reframe the SSS as a PERCEIVED CAPACITY SCALE
If you want this to survive academic scrutiny, you need one structural correction:
The SSS must measure perceived somatic regulation efficacy, not actual autonomic control.
That single change resolves 80% of the credibility risk.

Revised Construct Definition (critical)
Somatic Sovereignty (redefined)
The self-reported perceived ability to maintain awareness, emotional regulation, and choice-consistent behavior under conditions of heightened physiological arousal.
This removes:
	•	unverifiable physiological claims
	•	implied causal control over autonomic functions
	•	hidden bio-deterministic assumptions

Second Issue: Item Wording Validity
Right now several items contain implicit claims of ability causality, e.g.:
	•	“I can slow my pulse within 2 minutes”
	•	“I can consciously dissolve clenching reflexes”
	•	“I can transition at will into deep relaxation”
These are better rewritten as:
Valid psychometric form:
	•	“I feel capable of influencing my breathing in ways that reduce stress”
	•	“I can notice and reduce muscular tension when I focus on it”
	•	“I am usually able to return to a calm state after stress”
This shifts from:
mechanical claim to: perceived efficacy
Which is standard in instruments like:
	•	GSES (General Self-Efficacy Scale)
	•	ERQ (Emotion Regulation Questionnaire)

Third Issue: Composite Score Problem
Your 0–100 normalization assumes linear construct equivalence.
But in psychometrics:
	•	interoception ≠ regulation ≠ behavioral inhibition
So a single composite score risks:
false unidimensionality
Fix options:
Either:
Option A (recommended)
Do NOT produce a single “sovereignty score”
Instead output:
	•	IA index
	•	DR index
	•	CP index
and explicitly avoid aggregation.
Option B (weaker but usable)
Create composite as:
latent factor estimate (post hoc, not arithmetic sum)
but only after factor analysis in pilot data.

Fourth Issue: “Clinical Escalation Flag”
This is currently:
ethically and diagnostically over-assertive
A self-report scale cannot responsibly generate:
“RED ZONE: immediate clinical escalation”
without:
	•	validated cutoff thresholds
	•	clinical sensitivity/specificity testing
	•	population norming
Safer alternative:
“Low-range score may indicate elevated distress or reduced perceived regulation capacity. Consider reviewing with a qualified professional if this aligns with lived impairment.”

What You Have (Important)
Despite these corrections, what you are building is structurally close to:
	•	HRV-adjacent self-regulation research tools
	•	CBT self-efficacy measurement frameworks
	•	interoceptive awareness inventories
	•	behavioral inhibition scales
That is a real research direction—but it must stay within:
“self-reported perceived capacity under stress”
or it will not pass methodological review.

